socket.close.1001: Going away - client or server is going away (e.g. server shutdown or client navigated away).
socket.close.1002: Protocol error - an endpoint is terminating the connection due to a protocol error.
socket.close.1003: Unsupported data - received data of a type it cannot accept (e.g., text-only endpoint received binary).
socket.close.1005: No status received - reserved. Used internally to indicate that no status code was provided.
socket.close.1006: Abnormal closure - reserved. Used to indicate abnormal disconnection (e.g., without a close frame).
socket.close.1007: Invalid payload data - received inconsistent or non-UTF-8 data when expected.
socket.close.1008: Policy violation - message violates endpoint's policy (e.g., too large, unauthorized format).
socket.close.1009: Message too big - message is too large for the endpoint to process.
socket.close.1010: Mandatory extension - client expected the server to negotiate one or more extensions, but server didn't.
socket.close.1011: Internal error - server encountered an unexpected condition that prevented it from fulfilling the request.
socket.close.1013: Try again later - server is temporarily unavailable.
socket.close.1014: Bad gateway - the server acting as a gateway received an invalid response.
socket.close.1015: TLS handshake failure - reserved. Indicates failure during TLS handshake.
